Create an ApplicationSet in the Asset Store (if not already done).

Fetch RODAN entitlements using the query string.

Add the resource and action to the existing ApplicationSet in the Asset Store.

Ensure the Asset Store updates reflect in the PlainID UI.

Create a dynamic group in PlainID for the Swarm group.

Create a policy in PlainID and link the resource, action, and group.

Verify that everything is set up correctly in PlainID.

Detailed Steps
Step 1: Create an ApplicationSet in the Asset Store
Since you've already created the ApplicationSet named "PPM" in the Asset Store, we can proceed to the next step. If not, you would create it using the following API call:

Method: POST

Endpoint: /asset/api/v1/application-sets

Headers: Content-Type: application/json

Body:

json
Copy code
{
  "applicationSet": "PPM",
  "applicationSetDescription": "PPM",
  "applicationSetCmdbApplicationInstances": [],
  "applicationSetResourceTypes": [],
  "cmdbApplicationId": "e8767abe4f348700c5ce44f18110c764",
  "cmdbApplicationDescription": "PPM"
}
Step 2: Fetch RODAN Entitlements
Fetch the entitlements from RODAN for the specified resource, action, and group.

Resource: /ppm/PPM/Administration/Resource
Action: View
Group: ppm-plainid-developers
Procedure:

Use the RODAN API to retrieve entitlements.

Example Query String:

javascript
Copy code
resource=/ppm/PPM/Administration/Resource&action=View
Expected Response:

json
Copy code
{
  "entitlements": {
    "entitlement": [
      {
        "resource": "/ppm/PPM/Administration/Resource",
        "action": "View",
        "group": "ppm-plainid-developers",
        "deny": "false"
      }
    ]
  }
}
Notes:

Ensure you have the necessary authentication and permissions to access the RODAN API.
If you encounter any issues, consult the RODAN API documentation or contact your internal support team.
Step 3: Add Resource and Action to the ApplicationSet in the Asset Store
Step 3.1: Create Resource Type (if not already exists)

Method: POST

Endpoint: /asset/api/v1/resources/resource-types

Headers: Content-Type: application/json

Body:

json
Copy code
{
  "applicationSet": "PPM",
  "cmdbApplicationId": "e8767abe4f348700c5ce44f18110c764",
  "resourceType": "RODAN",
  "resourceTypeDescription": "Resources from RODAN"
}
Notes:

If the resource type "RODAN" already exists, you can skip this step.
You can check existing resource types by fetching the ApplicationSet details.
Step 3.2: Add Resource to the ApplicationSet

Method: PUT

Endpoint: /asset/api/v1/resources

Query Parameters:

makefile
Copy code
applicationSet=PPM
cmdbApplicationId=e8767abe4f348700c5ce44f18110c764
resourceType=RODAN
Headers: Content-Type: application/json

Body:

json
Copy code
{
  "resourceValues": [
    "/ppm/PPM/Administration/Resource"
  ],
  "resourceAttributes": []
}
Notes:

Ensure the resource path matches exactly with the one used in RODAN.
You can add multiple resources by including them in the resourceValues array.
Step 3.3: Verify the Action Exists in the Asset Store

Depending on your Asset Store implementation, actions may be managed separately.
If actions need to be defined, ensure that the action "View" is available in the Asset Store.
Step 4: Ensure the Asset Store Updates Reflect in the PlainID UI
The Asset Store should synchronize with PlainID, making the new resource available.
Note: Synchronization may take some time depending on the system configuration.
Step 5: Create a Dynamic Group in PlainID
Check if the Group Exists:

Before creating the group, check if "ppm-plainid-developers" already exists in PlainID.
Create the Group (if not exists):

Method: POST

Endpoint: /api/groups

Headers:

Content-Type: application/json
Include authentication headers as required.
Body:

json
Copy code
{
  "name": "ppm-plainid-developers",
  "description": "Group for PPM PlainID Developers",
  "groupType": "swarm",
  "namespace": "global"
}
Notes:

Replace "namespace": "global" with the appropriate namespace if needed.
Ensure you have permissions to create groups in PlainID.
Step 6: Create a Policy in PlainID
Step 6.1: Create the Policy

Method: PUT

Endpoint: /rest/permission

Headers:

Content-Type: application/json
Include authentication headers.
Include the namespace header if required.
Body:

json
Copy code
{
  "objectType": "Policy",
  "name": "PPM-View-Access",
  "description": "Access policy for PPM View action",
  "namespace": "NamespaceID",  // Replace with the actual namespace ID
  "namespaceUsage": "PRIVATE",
  "active": true,
  "restricted": false
}
Notes:

Ensure the namespace is correctly specified.
The policy name should be unique within the namespace.
Step 6.2: Link Resources and Actions to the Policy

Retrieve IDs:

Policy ID: Obtained from the response when creating the policy.
Resource ID: Retrieve using the resource name /ppm/PPM/Administration/Resource.
Action ID: Retrieve the ID for the action "View" from PlainID.
Link the Resource and Action:

Method: POST

Endpoint: /rest/xresource/link

Headers:

Content-Type: application/json
Include authentication headers.
Body:

json
Copy code
[
  {
    "permission": "PolicyID",  // Replace with the actual policy ID
    "resources": [
      {
        "resource": "ResourceID",  // Replace with the actual resource ID
        "actions": ["ActionID"]    // Replace with the actual action ID
      }
    ]
  }
]
Notes:

Ensure all IDs are correctly retrieved and substituted in the body.
Step 7: Link the Dynamic Group to the Policy
Method: POST

Endpoint: /rest/permission/{PolicyID}/permissionRule/dynamic

Replace {PolicyID} with the actual policy ID.
Headers:

Content-Type: application/json
Include authentication headers.
Include namespace: NamespaceID if required.
Body:

json
Copy code
["GroupID"]
Notes:

Replace GroupID with the actual ID of the group "ppm-plainid-developers".
This links the group to the policy, granting access as defined.


